#1 Moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of lower rectum, status-post neoadjuvant chemoradiation therapy followed several months later by an abdominoperineal resection, here for FOLFOX6 adjuvant therapy.
#2 Neck pain post recent port placement
#3 History of nicotine addiction
#4 History of alcohol abuse with fatty liver disease
PLAN
At this time we would proceed with chemotherapy, FOLFOX6.  Side-effects were extensively discussed with Mr. Locke including, but not limited to, myelosuppression, life-threatening infections, neutropenia, tingling, numbness, both acute and chronic neurotoxicity, cardiac toxicity of 5-FU.  I have given him a counts letter to get a CBC next week to assess the degree of myelosuppression.  Should there be myelosuppression noted, we could omit bolus 5-FU.  Other side-effects including allergic reactions, fatigue, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea were also discussed at length with Mr. Locke.  For his neck pain, I have suggested that we could further evaluate to see if there is any evidence of internal hematoma that is compressing on his trachea, although the chest x-ray is not suggestive of any tracheal deviation.  He at this time is reluctant to proceed with further imaging and wishes to just observe.  I am comfortable with this approach.  I have instructed that he try warm compresses in this area.  The case was discussed with Dr. Stallings, who agrees with the aforementioned approach.  In addition, we feel that since his hemoglobin is stable it is unlikely that there is any big hematoma in that area.  Certainly, it is not evident externally.  I would see him again in two-weeks for the next cycle of FOLFOX provided there are no complications noted with the current one.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

